The "ape car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking for example the bee flight, can avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this little robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C is an extension of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the producer house.
During the flight, each water creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the eyes composed of bees, able to see in all directions with an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insects to fly without interruption in their personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they have defined as a location laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor on board that immediately allows to prevent collision.
"At the moment when it detects a obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of an ape and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at a straight or larger angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike an ape, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, and even diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and in the direction in which they can turn its wheels and not exploit endless directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the little robot could avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act by starting with this data.
It does not require the storage of information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruptions and with just a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, and not even mega."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instant prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be in the car series within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the typology with lithium ions.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in the path.
