The fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurers often refuse to enter into an insurance contract on the basis of data on the purchase of medicinal products from individuals.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription data of medicines depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick the author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the medicines.
Insurance companies are subject to the insurance rate and the amount payable in case of health claims of any customer and if they consider the risk to be too high they do not provide for insurance.
The customer had to make a medical visit a while ago and the contract was concluded only after the exam was completed.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer's identification code you can easily get information from the pharmacies on which medicine you bought in the last year and half and from this the program evidence of which disease and health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is in practice unregulatedly high and is classified into the highest risk category.
In trade there are several versions of the programme, some also determine the risk multiplier, so there is not much left to the insurer in addition to paper work, even if there are small difficulties.
Amongst the contrary, some medicines are usable for more purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraine or heat vapours, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance point of view - commercially, applies as a risk increase factor, the first two no.
For the request and data processing, companies were formed separately and these, before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, demand the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are obliged to do so even if so far they have not imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have also recently developed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data and in parallel control of usage will be more and more difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a proposal for a law which gives control powers to companies specialized in the data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the other data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
